surveys.narrative:
A targeted survey of the nearshore fish community in Lower Hay Lake was conducted by Fisheries Index of Biological Integrity (IBI) Program Staff starting August 1, 2018. Fourteen sampling sites were evenly spaced around the lake and each was sampled by backpack electrofishing and seining with a 15-foot or 50-foot seine, where possible. Backpack electrofishing and a 50-foot seine were used to sample at all 14 sites. Nearshore sampling captured 29 native species of fish including nine species that are intolerant of disturbance (Banded Killifish, Blackchin Shiner, Iowa Darter, Logperch, Longnose Dace, Mimic Shiner, Mottled Sculpin, Rock Bass, and Smallmouth Bass) and three species that are tolerant of disturbance (Black Bullhead, Fathead Minnow, and Green Sunfish).

Data from this targeted nearshore survey is combined with trap net and gill net data from a June 2018 standard survey to describe the fish community and provide a Fish-based Index of Biological Integrity (FIBI) score. The FIBI uses fish community data to measure a lake's health, and the types of fish species present can help identify any stressors that may be negatively affecting the lake environment. The FIBI score, composed of several fish community diversity and composition metrics, indicates the overall health of a lake by comparing it to what is expected for a healthy lake. The FIBI score for Lower Hay Lake from this survey is above an impairment threshold for aquatic life use determined for similar lakes and indicates an exceptional fish community is present in this lake. For additional information on the FIBI, search for "lake index of biological integrity" on the mndnr.gov website.

Data from this survey will contribute biological information about the health of the fish community to the Pine River Watershed assessment of surface waters process completed in coordination with MN Pollution Control Agency.

Night electrofishing was done on September 14, 2010 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes resulting from fry stocking. The total sample time was 2.0 hours. The YOY walleye catch was 14.5 fish/hour . These fish ranged from 5.7-7.3 inches and averaged 6.5 inches long. Walleyes age 1 and older were captured at a rate of 5.5 fish/hour. These fish ranged from 8.6-14.1 inches and averaged 10.7 inches long.

The current management plan calls for 5 million walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on October 1, 2019 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. The total sample time was 33 minutes, which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 9.1/hr. run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr. to 53.1/hr. run-time. The YOY walleyes ranged in size from 6.5" to 7.3" with a mean length of 6.8". Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 36.4/hr. run-time. They ranged in size from 8.2" to 11.8", with a mean length of 9.5".

The current management plan calls for 5 million walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 28, 2022 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. The total sample time was 42 minutes, which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 21.4/hour run-time. These fish ranged in size from 5.8" to 7.3". Previous catches have ranged from 0/hour to 53.1/hour run-time. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 4.3/hr. run-time. They ranged in size from 17.8" to 18.8", with a mean length of 18.2".

Lower Hay is a 685 acre lake and part of the 14,000 acre Whitefish chain of lakes. Development is heavy with 121 homes/cabins on four miles of shoreline.In 1995, walleyes, yellow perch, black bullheads and smallmouth bass were found in "low" numbers compared to similar type lakes. Bluegills, largemouth bass, rock bass and yellow bullheads were found in "high" numbers. Lake whitefish, tullibees, northern pike, white suckers, black crappies, bowfin (dogfish), brown bullheads and pumpkinseeds were found in "average" numbers.

Night electrofishing was done on September 25, 2013 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes that were stocked as fry into the Whitefish Chain in 2013. The total sample time was 48 minutes, resulting in a YOY walleye catch rate of 48.8/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr run-time (2000 & 2008) to 33.0/hr run-time (2003). These fish ranged in size from 5.0" to 7.5", with a mean length of 5.9". Walleye that were age 1 and older were captured at a rate of 13.8/hr run-time. These fish ranged in size from 7.9" to 16.5" and had a mean length of 9.5".

Night-time electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 23, 2014 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes that were stocked into the Whitefish Chain. There were 5,000,000 walleye fry stocked in the Whitefish Chain in 2014. The total sample time was 40 minutes which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 46.5/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 48.8/hr run-time. The YOY walleyes ranged in size from 4.8" to 7.2", with a mean length of 6.2". Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 6.0/hr run-time. They ranged in size from 9.5" to 27.7", with a mean length of 18.1".

There were 6.3 million walleye fry stocked into the Whitefish Chain in 2016. The current management plan calls for 5 million fry to be stocked annually with a provision to stock surplus hatchery fry as the Whitefish Chain is a source of walleye eggs for DNR hatchery production for local area and statewide stocking. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 20, 2016 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes resulting from natural reproduction and fry stocking. The total sample time was 35 minutes which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 53.1/hr. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 48.8/hr. The YOY walleyes ranged in size from 5.6" to 7.3", with an average length of 6.6". YOY walleye abundance can be an early indicator of year class strength. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 8.6/hr. They ranged in size from 8.6" to 13.9", with an average length of 11.2".

The current management plan calls for 5 million Walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Whitefish is also stocked in even numbered years with 2,714 lbs. of fingerlings; some of this stocking takes place at the Lower Hay access. Night electrofishing was conducted on September 18th, 2023, to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) Walleyes. The total sample time was 43 minutes, which resulted in a YOY Walleye catch rate of 7.0/hour run-time. These fish ranged in size from 6.4" to 7.1". Previous catches have ranged from 0/hour to 53.1/hour run-time. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 30.7/hr. run-time. They ranged in size from 7.4" to 9.5", with a mean length of 7.9".

A temperature-dissolved oxygen profile was collected in the deepest basin on Lower Hay Lake on August 15th, 2023 to evaluate the amount of cold, oxygenated water (i.e., oxythermal habitat) available to Lake Whitefish and Cisco, also known as Tullibee. Based on the profile, the top of the thermocline (i.e., the location in the water column with the sharpest transition from warm to cold water) occurred at approximately 17 feet. Dissolved oxygen decreased to below 3.0 mg/L at 95.8 feet, which was below the thermocline, at the time of sampling. The temperature at which dissolved oxygen decreased to below 3.0 mg/L (i.e., TDO3, a single variable to characterize oxythermal habitat) was 4.9?C (40.8?F).

TDO3 values cooler than 17.2?C for Lake Whitefish or 21.5?C for Cisco indicate that oxythermal conditions are favorable for these species. Dissolved oxygen concentrations below the thermocline indicate that suitable oxythermal habitat for these species was available across a range of depths at the time of sampling. Data collected in 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2001, 2002, and 2016 also indicated suitable oxythermal habitat. When adequate oxythermal habitat is available, Lake Whitefish or Cisco are not squeezed into unfavorable, warmer water conditions and therefore do not experience higher levels of stress.

The current management plan calls for 5 million walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 fry into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 26, 2018 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. The total sample time was 45 minutes, which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 29.3/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 53.1/hr run-time. The YOY walleyes ranged in size from 6.4" to 8.4" with an average length of 7.4". Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 8.0/hr run-time. They ranged in size from 9.3" to 19.0", with an average length of 15.7".

The current management plan calls for 5 million walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Due to Covid restrictions during spring of 2020, no walleye fry were stocked in 2020. However, night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 16, 2020 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes from natural reproduction. The total sample time was 1 hour and 24 minutes, which resulted in no YOY walleye being caught. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 53.1/hr run-time. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 4.3/hr run-time. They ranged in size from 8.7" to 20.9", with a mean length of 12.6".

Lower Hay Lake is a 685 acre lake that is part of the 14,000 acre Whitefish chain of lakes. Development is heavy with 121 homes/cabins on four miles of shoreline. The littoral area (area 15 feet deep or less) is 215 acres or 31% of the surface area. Maximum depth is 100 feet and water clarity is good, with a secchi disc reading of 11 feet.In 2000, bluegill,largemouth bass, pumpkinseed and rock bass sampled in high numbers. Walleyes, shorthead redhorse, tullibee, yellow bullheads, black bullheads and green sunfish were taken in low numbers. Lake whitefish, northern pike, white suckers, yellow perch, black crappies, bowfin, and brown bullheads were taken in average numbers. All species exhibited good growth rates.Walleye were netted at a rate of 3.1/gillnet and northern pike were netted at 6.11 /gillnet. Mean weights were 1.94 pounds and 2.76 pounds respectively.Bluegills remain to be present in very high numbers and 22% of those fish sampled were 7.0 inches or greater in length.

Lower Hay Lake, part of the Whitefish Chain, is a 685 acre lake in northern Crow Wing County. Maximum depth is 100 ft. Lower Hay is highly developed with 112 homes around its 4.2 miles of shoreline. A DNR access is located on the south shore with access also possible through a channel from Whitefish Lake. Water clarity was good with a secchi reading of 12 feet.

The northern pike catch rate of 15.7/ gillnet was well above average, and the highest to date. Average size was 18.8 inches and 1.5 lbs. Northern pike over 24 inches made up only 8% of the population. Growth was above average compared to area lakes.

Walleyes were caught at below average numbers at a rate of 1.7/gillnet, although average size was nice at 20.3 inches and 3.3 lbs. Walleyes are stocked annually as fry and every other year as fingerlings into the Whitefish Chain.

Bluegills were caught in above average numbers at 49.7/ trapnet. Size should be very acceptable to anglers with 85% of the population over 7 inches, and 29% over 8 inches with the largest measuring 9.7 inches. Average weight was 0.4 lbs. Anglers need to practice selective harvest to protect the quality size of bluegills.

Yellow perch were caught in the lowest numbers to date at 0.6/gillnet. Yellow perch are an important prey species especially for walleyes and northern pike. Other fish captured included black crappie, hybrid sunfish, lake whitefish, pumpkinseed, largemouth bass, rock bass, tullibee (cisco), white sucker, yellow bullhead, bowfin (dogfish), brown bullhead, greater redhorse, silver redhorse and shorthead redhorse. During near shore electrofishing and seining for IBI an additional ten species of fish were captured.

While the Lower Hay management plan doesn't call for any direct walleye stocking, it is connected to Whitefish which is stocked annually with fry and every other year with fingerlings. Fish are regularly stocked from the Lower Hay access as it is one of the better accesses on the chain. Walleyes were caught in below average numbers in 2018 (1.5/gill net), although size was quite good, with an average size of 20.1" and all of the fish measuring over 15".

Northern pike numbers continue to be high at 14.1/gill net, but size is relatively small. Average length was 19.7" and only 9% of the fish were 24" or larger. Lakes in this part of the state have a new northern pike regulation enacted in 2018: possession limit of 10 with not more than 2 over 26". All from 22"-26" must be immediately released. Please refer to the current Minnesota Fishing Regulations for additional information.

Largemouth bass numbers for the Whitefish Chain, which includes Lower Hay, were 68.8/hr run-time during night electrofishing. Average length was 13.5". Five smallmouth bass were also netted while electrofishing the chain. All but one were over 17".

Panfish numbers were moderately low with 5.8 bluegills/trap net. Average size was 6.5" and 54% of the fish were 7" or larger. Black crappies were sampled at a rate of 0.7/trap net with 75% measuring at least 8".

Lake whitefish and tullibee (cisco), which are important forage fish for walleye and northern pike, were both caught in Lower Hay. Numbers were average for both whitefish (1.6/gill net) and tullibee (4.1/gill net). Average size was 15.1" for whitefish and only 8.9" for tullibee.

Lower Hay is a 685 acre lake that is part of the 14,000 acre Whitefish chain of lakes. Development is heavy with 121 homes/cabins on four miles of shoreline in 1995. The littoral area (area 15 feet deep or less) is 215 acres, or 31% of the surface area. Maximum depth is 100 feet and water clarity is good, with a secchi disc reading of 13 feet in mid-June, 2005.In 2005, lake whitefish, black crappie, bluegill, bowfin, largemouth bass and rock bass were sampled in high numbers. Walleye, yellow bullhead and yellow perch were sampled in low numbers. Northern pike, black bullhead, brown bullhead, tullibee, white sucker, pumpkinseed and shorthead redhorse were taken in average numbers compared to similar type lakes. Growth rates for all species were generally good.The walleye catch was 1.08/GN. Size averaged 17.4 inches and 2.3 pounds. The northern pike catch was 8.5/GN. Their size averaged 22.1 inches and 2.5 pounds. Bluegills were present in high numbers but 49% were at least 7 inches long. The black crappie catch was also high and 55% were at least 8 inches long.

Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 17, 2015 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. There were 5,000,000 walleye fry stocked into the Whitefish Chain in 2015. The total sample time was 38 minutes which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 11.1/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 48.8/hr run-time. The YOY walleyes ranged in size from 5.7" to 7.8", with an average size of 6.9". Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 9.5/hr run-time. They ranged in size from 7.5" to 12.4", with an average size of 8.7".

The current management plan calls for 5 million walleye fry to be stocked annually into Whitefish and another 880,000 into Cross, both of which are connected to Lower Hay. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 22, 2021 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. The total sample time was 33 minutes, which resulted in a YOY walleye catch rate of 1.8/hour run-time (1 fish). Previous catches have ranged from 0/hour to 53.1/hour run-time. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 12.7/hr. run-time. They ranged in size from 9.3" to 18.2", with a mean length of 11.9".

Night electrofishing was done on September 19, 2012 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes that were stocked as fry into the Whitefish Chain in 2012. The total sample time was 55 minutes, resulting in a YOY walleye catch rate of 20.7/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr run-time (2000 & 2008) to 33.0/hr run-time (2003). These fish ranged in size from 5.5" to 7.3". Only one walleye was caught that wasn't YOY and it was 15.2" long.

Nearly 7.2 million walleye fry were stocked into the Whitefish Chain, of which Lower Hay is a part of, in 2017. As was the case in 2017, surplus fry often get stocked into this chain as it is the source of the walleye egg take for the Brainerd Area. Night electrofishing was conducted on Lower Hay Lake on September 26, 2017 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes. Only one YOY fish was captured, measuring 6.6" long. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr to 53.1/hr. Walleyes that were age 1 and older were sampled at a rate of 13.3/hr. They ranged in size from 8.5" to 23.9", with an average length of 13.7".

Fish species exhibiting high numbers were northern pike, yellow bullhead, rock bass, pumpkinseed and bluegill. Growth rates were average for all species sampled except for bluegill which indicated slow growth. The fish population levels in numbers and average size of fish as determined from the range of median values for appropriate types of gear are indicated in the following table. High population levels are indicated by catch rates above the third quartile and low population levels by catch rates below the first quartile. Catch rates falling between the first and third quartiles are indicative of average, or normal numbers for a particular species. Average size of fish for a particular species or mean weight per individual fish are listed as small, average and large. Average size is indicated by mean weight falling between the first and third quartile. Small size is indicated by mean weight below the first quartile and large size by mean weight above the third quartile.

Night electrofishing was done on September 22, 2011 to monitor the abundance of young-of-the-year (YOY) walleyes that were stocked as fry in 2011. The total sample time was 1 hour and 57 minutes, resulting in a YOY walleye catch rate of 3.1/hr run-time. Previous catches have ranged from 0/hr run-time (2000 & 2008) to 33.0/hr run-time (2003). These fish ranged in size from 6.3" to 6.5". Walleyes that were age 1 and older were captured at a rate of 14.4/hr run-time. These fish ranged in size from 7.0" to 28.5" and had a mean length of 11.3".
